summary.seg: This manuscript, probably dating from the tenth century, contains the psalms and canticles, with interlinear and marginal glosses in Latin and medieval Irish. Its designation as the ‘Southampton’ Psalter is misleading, as it has no connection with the place Southampton, and although conveyed to St John’s by the Earl of Southampton, it came from the library of his friend William Crashaw rather than his own collection. This psalter is valued by Irish scholars as a source for early medieval Irish language glosses, and by art historians for its decoration, being notable for three full-page illustrations and the three elaborately decorated introductory pages which face them at the divisions of each set of 50 psalms. The precise location and date of its manufacture are obscure.

supportDesc.foliation: Medieval foliation in the hand of John Whytefelde, Librarian of Dover Priory, beginning at folio 4 and running to 101.

layoutDesc.layout: A single column layout, with generous spacing. The pattern of decoration is consistent throughout the volume, suggesting a work planned with the visual in mind, though possibly influenced by the examplar (unknown) on which it drew. The text is glossed throughout, with glosses spilling into the margins. Most glosses are in Latin, some in vernacular Irish. The 150 psalms are divided into three groups of 50.

handDesc.handNote: 10th century, finely written. Insular half-uncial and Insular miniscule scripts in varying sizes are used to indicate the relative importance of texts. Besides the main scribe, three or four other hands have been identified.

decoDesc.decoNote: Three full page illustrations depicting David having fought a lion, the Cruxificion, and David’s victory over Goliath, preceding Psalm 1, Psalm 51 and Psalm 101 respectively. Facing each full page illustration is an elaborately decorated introductory page with a large initial incorporating a beast on a background of interlaced paws and tails. These introductory pages have an interlaced border. Smaller ornamented capitals mark the start of each Psalm, alternating between ‘ribbon animal’ and ‘knotted wire’ decorations. The initials at the start of each verse are simply decorated with a fill of alternating colours. The palette throughout consists of yellow, brownish purple, lighter purple, and orange.

physDesc.additions: College bookplate on flyleaf. Pasted paper spine label.

bindingDesc.p: Diced Russian early-nineteenth-century (the associated flyleaf has been dated by its watermark to 1818).

history.provenance: Given to the Library by Thomas Wriothesley, earl of Southampton Wriothesley, Thomas in 1635, from the library of William Crashaw Crashaw, William . On folio 1v is a sixteenth-century inscription of R. Benet, who appears to have been Mayor of Romney. Benet’s name occurs in other manuscripts collected by Crashaw. A partially erased inscription in the bottom margin of folio 5r reads ‘’Jhon Hurter [Hurtwell?] pbr’. According to John Whytefelde’s catalogue of 1389, this manuscript bore the shelf-mark A:V: in the collection of St Martin’s Priory, Dover; this shelf-mark appears both on the reverse of the original front flyleaf and in the bottom margin of folio 3r. Twelfth-century corrections in an English hand lead O’Neill to suggest that the manuscript may have arrived in Dover from Canterbury.

recordHist.source: This record draws on M.R. James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of St John’s College, Cambridge and the introduction to Padraig O’Neill’s edition of the manuscript.
